<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-absolute-relative-and-percentage-errors" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Absolute, Relative, and Percentage Errors</title>
    <!--  -->
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurement and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.1 Approximation and Errors
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title> 
                    <p>
                        Determine absolute, relative and percentage errors from measurements
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        11
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>

    <!-- [LP] Add guidance on activity -->

    <axiom component="lesson-plan" xml:id="lesson-plan-locker-discovery">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery: Absolute and Relative Error</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    40 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    Students will discover how to calculate absolute differences between measured values and a known true value, and express these differences as a fraction of the true value.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Ensure every group has access to a standard 15 cm ruler. Let students run the three trials independently without interfering. When they discover that their results vary, introduce Mr. Mbasu's 90 cm measurement as the official benchmark (true value) to anchor the subtraction and division steps.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <activity>
        <p>
            Your school locker serves as both your writing surface and your storage space. Because you use it every day, we will use it to test for measurement.
        </p>
        <p>
            <term>Work in Groups</term> of <m>3 - 4</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            Clear the surface of three lockers. Use a <m>15</m> cm ruler to measure the total length of each locker and record the observation in the table below.
        </p>

        <figure xml:id="fig-three-lockers">
            <caption>Lockers to be measured.</caption>

            <image>
                <latex-image>
                    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.08]
                    \draw[thick, fill=yellow!30]
                        (0,60) rectangle (90,67);

                    \node at (45,63.5) {15 cm ruler};
                    \draw[thick] (0,0) rectangle (90,50);
                    \draw[thick] (0,50) -- (10,60) -- (100,60) -- (90,50);
                    \draw[thick] (90,0) -- (100,10) -- (100,60);

                    \node at (45,25) {Locker};
                    \draw[->] (0,-10) -- (90,-10);
                    \node at (45,-18) {Length};

                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
        </figure>
        
        <tabular left="medium" right="medium" top="medium" bottom="medium">
            <row header="yes">
                <cell>Locker</cell>
                <cell>Length (cm)</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell><m>1</m></cell>
                <cell>?</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                <cell>?</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                <cell>?</cell>
            </row>
        </tabular>
        <p>
            During the design, the school gave a working measurement of the locker length as your second locker Length. For this activity, we will use your second locker length as our working length.  
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li>
                    <p>
                        What is your group's working length of the locker?
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        What is the difference between your second locker Length and the working length of the locker?
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        What is the difference between your first locker Length and the working length of the locker?
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                         What is the difference between your third locker Length and the working  length of the locker?
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                       Divide (b) by the working length?
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                         Divide (c) by the working length?
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Find the percentages of these Divisions in (e) and (f). Which one is greater and why?
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </activity>


     


    <!-- [LP] Add guidance on structured lesson plan-->

    <axiom component="lesson-plan" xml:id="lesson-plan-locker-structured-instruction">
        <title>Structured Instruction: Formalizing Error Calculations</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Suggested Time</title>
                    <p>
                        15 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Objective</title>
                    <p>
                        To formalize the definitions and formulas for Absolute Error, Relative Error, and Percentage Error using the locker data.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Key Takeaways &amp; Teacher Connection</title>
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Connecting to Learner Work:</alert> Use the differences calculated in questions (b), (c), and (d) to define <alert>Absolute Error</alert> as <m>|\text{Measured Value} - \text{True Value}|</m>. Point out that Mr. Mbasu's <m>90</m> cm measurement is the true value.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Formalizing Relative Error:</alert> Connect questions (e) and (f) to the concept of <alert>Relative Error</alert>. Explain that dividing the absolute error by the true value shows the size of the error relative to the object being measured.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Formalizing Percentage Error:</alert> Use question (g) to define <alert>Percentage Error</alert> by multiplying the relative error by <m>100\%</m>. Explain that a larger percentage means a less accurate measurement process.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>

    <insight>
        <p>
            <term>Absolute error:</term> is the magnitude of the difference between the measured value and the working value.
        </p>
        <p>
            <md>
                <mrow> \text{Absolute error} = \amp \; |\text{measured value} - \text{working value}| </mrow>
            </md>
            
        </p>
        <p>
            Sometimes a measurement is given without stating the absolute error. In such cases, the absolute error is found by taking half of the smallest unit to which the value has been measured or rounded.
        </p>
        <p>
            For example, if we measure Yasmin's height as <m>1.70</m> m, the smallest unit of measurement is <m>0.01</m> m (since we have <m>2</m> decimal places), hence the absolute error is <m>0.005</m> m. 
        </p>
        <p>
            <term>Relative error:</term> is the quotient of the absolute error and the working value.
        </p>
        <p>
            <md>
                <mrow>\text{Relative error} = \amp \; \frac{\text{absolute error}}{\text{working value}} </mrow>
            </md>
            
        </p>
        <p>
            <term>Percentage error:</term> is the ratio of the absolute error and the working value multiplied by <m>100 \%</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            <md>
                <mrow>\text{Percentage error} = \amp \; \frac{\text{absolute error}}{\text{working value}} \; \times 100 \% </mrow>
                <mrow> = \amp \; \text{Relative error} \times 100 \% </mrow>
            </md>
            
        </p>
    </insight>

    <!-- Add further instruction (not in a block) to develop ideas as needed -->

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- Add at least 3 examples -->
     <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                The capacity of a pumpkin is stated as <m>2,000</m> millilitres to the nearest <m>10</m> millilitres. Find:
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The limit within which the capacity lies.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The percentage error.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The limit within which the capacity lies.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Absolute error is <m>\frac{1}{2} \times 10 = 5 \;\text{ml} </m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Lowest possible capacity is <m>2,000 \;\text{ml} - 5\;\text{ml}\; = 1,995 \;\text{ml} </m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                           Highest possible capacity is <m>2,000 \;\text{ml} + 5\;\text{ml}\; = 2,005 \;\text{ml} </m>  
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The percentage error.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow> 
                                \text{Percentage error} \; \amp = \; \frac{\text{absolute error}}{\text{actual measurement}} \; \times 100 \% </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = \; \frac{5 \; \text{ml}}{2,000 \;\text{ml}}\; \times 100 \% </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = \; 0.25 \% </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
     </example>
     <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                The thickness of a coin is <m>0.20</m> cm.
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            What is the percentage error?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            What would be the percentage error if its thickness was stated as <m>0.2</m> cm?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Since we are told the thickness is <m>0.20</m> cm, with two decimal places, the smallest unit of measurement is <m>0.01</m>. Hence the actual thickness must be between <m>0.195</m> cm and <m>0.205</m> cm. To get the absolute error, we half the smallest unit of measurement:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow> \text{Absolute error} \; \amp = \; \frac{1}{2} \times 0.01 </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = \; 0.005 </mrow>
                                <mrow> \text{Percentage error} \; \amp = \; \frac{0.005}{0.20} \times 100 \% </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = \; 2.5 \% </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The smallest unit of measurement is <m>0.1</m>.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow> \text{Absolute error} \; \amp = \; \frac{1}{2} \times 0.1 </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = \; 0.05 \;\text{cm}</mrow> 
                                <mrow> \text{Percentage error} \; \amp = \; \frac{0.05}{0.2} \times 100 \% </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = \; 25 \% </mrow>
                            </md>
                            
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
     </example>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/assessment-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- If STACK questions are included, uncomment this: -->

    <!-- <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/checkpoint.ptx" /> -->

    <!-- Add STACK exercises if made -->

    <!-- Add static exercises -->
     <exercises>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Find the absolute error, relative error, and percentage error for each of the following measurements:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m> 45.138 \;\text{s}</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m> 0.45 \;\text{g} </m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m> 7.62 \;\text{l} </m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>12.004 \;\text{cm}</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>2505 \;\text{tonnes}</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>0.005</m> ; <m>0.0001</m>, and <m>0.011 \%</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>0.005</m> ; <m>0.0111</m>, and <m>1.11 \%</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                               <m>0.005</m> ; <m>0.0007</m>, and <m>0.066 \%</m> 
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>0.0005</m> ; <m>0.00004</m>, and <m>0.0042 \%</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>0.5</m> ; <m>0.0002</m>, and <m>0.02 \%</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    The thickness of a book was measured to the nearest <m>0.02</m> cm as <m>8.0</m> cm. What is the percentage error? 
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>0.125 \%</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                  An angle was measured to the nearest degree as <m>40^\circ</m>. Calculate:  
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                The maximum possible value of the stated angle.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                               The minimum possible value of the stated angle. 
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                The percentage error
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                              <m>40.5 ^\circ</m>  
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>39.5 ^\circ</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>1.25 \%</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
     </exercises>


    <!-- [LP] Add information on how to differentiate  -->

    <axiom component="lesson-plan" xml:id="lesson-plan-locker-differentiation">
        <title>Differentiation</title>

        <table>
            <title>Differentiation Strategies for Error Analysis Activity</title>
            <tabular halign="left" top="medium" bottom="medium" left="medium" right="medium">
                <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                    <cell>Learner Group</cell>
                    <cell>Strategy &amp; Learning Experience</cell>
                </row>
                <row bottom="minor">
                    <cell><alert>Struggling Learners (Support)</alert></cell>
                    <cell>
                        Provide a structured worksheet that separates the subtraction step (Absolute Error) from the division step (Relative Error). Use color-coded blocks to show where to plug in the student measurement and Mr. Mbasu's <m>90</m> cm benchmark.
                    </cell>
                </row>
                <row bottom="minor">
                    <cell><alert>On-Level Learners (Core)</alert></cell>
                    <cell>
                        The core lesson activities as described above, calculating the differences, executing the divisions, converting the results into percentages, and interpreting which trial had the greatest error.
                    </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><alert>Advanced Learners (Challenge)</alert></cell>
                    <cell>
                        Ask them to determine what the maximum allowable absolute error would be if a student wanted to keep their total percentage error strictly under <m>1\%</m> for this specific locker length.
                    </cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>
    </axiom>

